\begin_layout Abstract
This paper presents a comprehensive packet loss concealment (PLC) system designed for real-time networked audio applications,
 featuring adaptive queue management and autoregressive prediction.
 The proposed 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Regulator
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 architecture combines multi-threaded packet buffering with Burg algorithm-based audio prediction to maintain continuous audio playback despite network packet loss.
 Key innovations include an adaptive worker thread that dynamically adjusts queue target sizes based on underrun patterns,
 per-channel autoregressive modeling for high-quality audio prediction,
 and comprehensive real-time performance monitoring.
 The system supports multiple audio channels,
 variable bit depths,
 and different frame sizes while maintaining low-latency operation suitable for interactive audio applications.
 Experimental evaluation demonstrates effective concealment of packet losses up to [X]% with minimal perceptual artifacts,
 while the adaptive queue management reduces underruns by [Y]% compared to fixed-size buffering approaches.
 The architecture's modular design enables deployment across various network audio scenarios,
 from music performance to voice communication systems.
 Statistical analysis reveals consistent performance under varying network conditions,
 with automatic adaptation to network jitter and variable latency patterns.
 The implementation provides a practical solution for maintaining audio quality in unreliable network environments while preserving the real-time constraints essential for interactive audio applications.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Introduction
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Network audio applications face significant challenges when operating over unreliable networks where packet loss,
 jitter,
 and variable latency can severely degrade audio quality
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Perkins2003,Schulzrinne2003"

\end_inset

.
 Traditional approaches to handling packet loss in audio streams typically involve either simple silence insertion,
 packet repetition or basic interpolation techniques,
 all of which produce audible artifacts that compromise the listening experience
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Jiang2002,Sanneck2000"

\end_inset

.
 For interactive applications such as networked music performance,
 voice communication,
 and remote audio collaboration,
 maintaining continuous,
 high-quality audio output is critical for user experience and application viability
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Rottondi2016,Carot2009"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The problem becomes particularly acute in real-time scenarios where buffering must be minimized to maintain interactive responsiveness
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Claypool1999"

\end_inset

.
 Unlike streaming applications that can afford larger buffers to smooth over network irregularities,
 interactive audio applications require solutions that balance audio quality preservation with minimal latency penalties
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Bolot1999"

\end_inset

.
 This necessitates sophisticated packet loss concealment strategies that can predict missing audio content with sufficient quality to mask brief interruptions.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Burg's algorithm is a maximum entropy method for autoregressive spectral estimation that has been deployed in speech coding and audio signal processing applications
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Burg1975,Markel1976"

\end_inset

.
 This paper introduces a novel packet loss concealment architecture with Burg as its prediction mechanism and 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Regulator
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 as the engine that adapts to incoming packet flows.
 The system is suited for use by various kinds of endpoints,
 including both peer-to-peer and hub-and-spoke (server-mediated) topologies
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Lazzaro2001"

\end_inset

.
 Uncompressed audio 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

rooms
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 in the cloud can be engineered to serve large aggregates of clients using the solution.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The name 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Regulator
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 is loosely inspired by an analogy to the regulators used in SCUBA breathing apparatus.
 It takes after the concept that the diver pulls air from a flow being pushed by the tank pressure.
 If the flow slackens the demand valve engages but if the flow exceeds demand pressure relief occurs.
\end_layout

